### Technical Details

**Before (11 lines):**
```cpp
dep_tracker::dep_tracker(unsigned num_bits) {
    unsigned words = (num_bits + 31) / 32;
    m_bits.resize(words, 0);
}

dep_tracker::dep_tracker(unsigned num_bits, unsigned set_bit) {
    unsigned words = (num_bits + 31) / 32;  // Duplicate calculation
    m_bits.resize(words, 0);                // Duplicate resize
    if (set_bit < num_bits) {
        unsigned word_idx = set_bit / 32;
        unsigned bit_idx = set_bit % 32;
        m_bits[word_idx] = 1u << bit_idx;
    }
}
```

**After (9 lines):**
```cpp
dep_tracker::dep_tracker(unsigned num_bits) {
    unsigned words = (num_bits + 31) / 32;
    m_bits.resize(words, 0);
}

dep_tracker::dep_tracker(unsigned num_bits, unsigned set_bit) : dep_tracker(num_bits) {
    if (set_bit < num_bits) {
        unsigned word_idx = set_bit / 32;
        unsigned bit_idx = set_bit % 32;
        m_bits[word_idx] = 1u << bit_idx;
    }
}
```

The delegating constructor first calls `dep_tracker(num_bits)` to initialize the bit vector, then continues with setting the specific bit. This is semantically identical to the original code but eliminates duplication.

### Review Focus

Please verify:
